# Networking Cheat Sheet

##  Common Commands

### Windows
- `ipconfig` → Show basic IP configuration
- `ipconfig /all` → Show detailed network info
- `ping 8.8.8.8` → Test connectivity to Google DNS
- `tracert google.com` → Trace route to a domain
- `netstat -an` → Show active connections and listening ports

### Linux
- `ifconfig` → Show interface configuration
- `ip addr show` → Display IP addresses
- `ping -c 4 8.8.8.8` → Ping 4 times
- `traceroute google.com` → Trace packet path
- `netstat -tuln` → List listening ports
- `ss -tuln` → Modern alternative to netstat

---

##  Subnetting Quick Reference

| CIDR | Subnet Mask     | # of Hosts | Notes                  |
|------|-----------------|------------|------------------------|
| /30  | 255.255.255.252 | 2 usable   | Point‑to‑point links   |
| /29  | 255.255.255.248 | 6 usable   | Small LAN segments     |
| /28  | 255.255.255.240 | 14 usable  | Small office networks  |
| /24  | 255.255.255.0   | 254 usable | Common home/office LAN |
| /16  | 255.255.0.0     | 65,534     | Large enterprise nets  |
| /8   | 255.0.0.0       | 16,777,214 | Very large networks    |

---

##  Troubleshooting Checklist
1. Check cables/Wi‑Fi connection
2. Verify IP address and gateway
3. Ping your gateway
4. Ping external site (e.g., 8.8.8.8)
5. Use traceroute to find where packets drop
